{
  "texts": [
    "Mathematically, density (Rp) in a hypergraph can be defined as the ratio of the number of hyperedges (E) to the possible number of hyperedges among the nodes (N) in a subgraph:",
    "This formula calculates the density for directed graphs, representing how closely knit (or dense) a relational frame cluster is, i.e., how many actual relational frame connections exist versus how many could possibly exist.",
    "Relational volume R v can be conceptualized as the total number of nodes and hyperedges within a cluster.",
    "It can reflect the amount of relational frame interactions within that part of the network, denoted as Rv N E D E.",
    "Here, α and β are scaling factors that adjust the relative importance of the number of nodes (N) versus the number of edges (E)."
  ]
}